I just mean this stuff:
```
    namespace impl 
    {    
        template <typename T, typename int_<decltype(&T::get_learning_rate_multiplier)>::type = 0> 
        double get_learning_rate_multiplier (
            const T& obj, 
            special_
        ) { return obj.get_learning_rate_multiplier(); }

        template <typename T>
        double get_learning_rate_multiplier ( const T& , general_) { return 1; } 
    }    
    template <typename T>
    double get_learning_rate_multiplier(const T& obj) { return impl::get_learning_rate_multiplier(obj, special_()); }
```
It uses SFINAE (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Substitution_failure_is_not_an_error) to select which overload of `get_learning_rate_multiplier` to use. The key bit here is `int_<decltype(&T::get_learning_rate_multiplier)>::type`, which is an error if `T::get_learning_rate_multiplier` doesn't exist.

