Given the performance constraints we're seeing on variadic indexing, I am somewhat inclined to remove variadic indexing and just supply `operator()` overloads for 1, 2, 3, and 4-dimensional ManagedArrays (similar to the `IndexND` approach of the previous codebase) and require vector notation for anything higher. The operator overload would become considerably simpler and more maintainable (though more repetitive), and it wouldn't cause these performance issues (as far as I can tell):
```c++
// 4D case
inline T &operator()(int i, int j, int k, int l)
{
    return (*this)({i, j, k, l});
}
```

I would include up to 4D so that we can handle cubatic tensors, and that's the highest dimensionality I'm aware of in freud.

