Hmm not 100% sure how to do it/if it's possible. Afaik boxed closures will always need a static lifetime. It might be possible to not box the closures, which would be great. They'll still need to be behind a pointer of some kind because they are unsized. So something like having the callbacks be `&'a dyn FnMut(SBP)`.  So changing

```rust
self.callbacks
    .entry(M::message_type())
    .or_default()
    .push(Box::new(move |msg: SBP| {
        let msg: M = msg.try_into().unwrap();
        func(msg)
    }));
```

to 

```rust 
self.callbacks
    .entry(M::message_type())
    .or_default()
    .push(&move |msg: SBP| {
        let msg: M = msg.try_into().unwrap();
        func(msg)
    });
```

Would let us drop `'static` in favor of generic lifetime `'a`. But, because we actually are storing a new closure rather than the one that was passed by the users you'll get a `temporary value dropped while borrowed` error. Still might be possible just not immediately obvious how to do it

